INSERT INTO `my_bl_post` VALUES(546, 'Yii guide Chapter 2 Fundamentals', '### Mainternance mode\r\nto put application to mainternance mode, specify `CWebApplication::catchAllRequest` property in configuration\r\n\r\n### Action\r\nto define a new action class:\r\n\r\n```php\r\nclass UpdateAction extends CAction {\r\n	public function run() {\r\n		// place the action logic here\r\n	}\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nto add action to controller:\r\n\r\n```php\r\nclass PostController extends CController {\r\n	public function actions() {\r\n		return array(\r\n			''edit'' =>’ application.controllers.post.UpdateAction’ ,\r\n		);\r\n	}\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Action parameter\r\n```php\r\nclass PostController extends CController {\r\n    public function actionCreate(array $categories) {\r\n        // Yii will make sure that $categories is an array\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\nif `$GET[''categories'']` is a simple string, it will be converted into an array consisting of that string\r\n\r\n### Production mode\r\nset `YII_DEBUG` to false\r\n\r\n### Set default controller for application\r\nin config file `defaultController` property\r\n\r\n### Application base directory\r\nit is `protected` directory, to change its path, set config `basePath` property\r\n\r\n### Preloading application component\r\nsome application components may not loaded if they weren''t accessed, to force creating, use `preload` config\r\n\r\n### Application life cycle\r\nRead it to know how to attach event or debug. When handling a user request, an application will undergo the following life cycle:\r\n\r\n1. Pre-initialize the application with CApplication::preinit();\r\n2. Set up the error handling;\r\n3. Register core application components;\r\n4. Load application configuration;\r\n5. Initialize the application with CApplication::init()\r\n	* Register application behaviors;\r\n	* Load static application components;\r\n6. Raise an onBeginRequest event;\r\n7. Process the user request:\r\n	* Collect information about the request;\r\n	* Create a controller;\r\n	* Run the controller;\r\n8. Raise an onEndRequest event;\r\n\r\n### Controller default action\r\nsetting default action for each controller: `CController::defaultAction` property\r\n\r\n### Route\r\nmake route case sensitive `CUrlManager::caseSensitive`\r\n\r\n### Filter\r\nFilter is a piece of code that is configured to be executed before and/or after a controller action executes.\r\n\r\nA filter can be defined as a controller class method. The method name must begin with filter.\r\n```php\r\npublic function filterAccessControl($filterChain) {\r\n	// call $filterChain->run() to continue filter and action execution\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nTo apply filters to actions, we need to override the CController::filters() method. The method should return an array of filter configurations\r\n```php\r\nclass PostController extends CController {\r\n    \r\n    public function filters() {\r\n        return array(\r\n            ''postOnly + edit, create'',\r\n            array(\r\n                ''application.filters.PerformanceFilter - edit, create'',\r\n                ''unit'' => ''second''\r\n            )\r\n        );\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\nUsing the plus and the minus operators, we can specify which actions the filter should and should not be applied to. \r\n\r\nIn the above, the postOnly filter will be applied to the edit and create actions, while PerformanceFilter filter will be applied to all actions EXCEPT edit and create. \r\n\r\nIf neither plus nor minus appears in the filter configuration, the filter will be applied to all actions.\r\n\r\n### Widget\r\nIt is a component that is mainly for presentational purposes. A widget is a complex, self-contained, reusable user interface (datepicker, input,..)\r\n\r\n### Convention\r\nVariable and function names should have their first word all in lower-case, in order to differentiate from class names (e.g. `$basePath`, `runController()`)\r\n\r\nPrivate class member prefix with underscore (e.g. `$ actionList`)\r\n\r\nDatabase convention:\r\n\r\n- table name and column name in lower case\r\n- word separated by underscore\r\n- table name use singular. e.g.  `user(name, chinese_name)`\r\n\r\n### Change runtime directory path\r\nIn configuration file, use setting `CApplication::runtimePath`\r\n\r\n### Best MVC Practices\r\n\r\nA Web application consists of several subapplications, such as:\r\n\r\n- frontend: a public-facing website for normal end users;\r\n- backend: a website that exposes administrative functionality for managing the application. This is usually restricted to administrative staff;\r\n- console: an application consisting of console commands to be run in a terminal window or as scheduled jobs to support the whole application;\r\n- Web API: providing interfaces to third parties for integrating with the application.\r\n\r\n#### Model\r\n- should contain business logic (e.g. validation rules) to ensure the represented data fulfills the design requirement\r\n- may contain code for manipulating data. This may make a model very fat\r\n- models should not contain logic that deals directly with end users:\r\n  - should not use $ GET, $ POST\r\n  - should avoid embedding HTML or other presentational code\r\n\r\nTo make model more maintainable:\r\n\r\n- Define a NewsBase model class which only contains code shared by different sub applications (e.g. front end, back end)\r\n- In each sub-application, define a News model by extending from NewsBase. Place all of the code that is specific to the sub-application in this News model.\r\n\r\n#### View\r\n- should mainly contain presentational code, such as HTML, and simple PHP code to traverse, format and render data\r\n- should avoid containing code that performs explicit DB queries. This is the model''s job\r\n- should avoid direct access to $ GET, $ POST, or other similar variables that represent\r\nthe end user request. This is the controller''s job\r\n- may access properties and methods of controllers and models directly\r\n\r\n#### Helper classes\r\nin views we often need some code snippets to do tiny tasks such as formatting data or generating HTML tags. \r\n\r\nRather than placing this code directly into the view files, a better approach is to place all of these code snippets in a view helper class. \r\n\r\nThen, just use the helper class in your view files (e.g. `CHtml`)\r\n\r\n#### Controller\r\n- may access `$_GET`, `$_POST` and other PHP variables that represent user requests\r\n- may create model instances and manage their life cycles\r\n- should avoid containing embedded SQL statements, which are better kept in models\r\n- should avoid containing any HTML or any other presentational markup. This is better kept in views.\r\n\r\nControllers are often very thin, containing probably only a few dozen lines of code\r\n\r\nWhile models are very fat, containing most of the code responsible for representing and manipulating the data', '2016-04-05 08:26:23', '2016-04-17 15:08:54', 0);
